    "narrative": "You're an **exploratory, project-driven user** who works on a focused set of projects — primarily a Bauhaus clock macOS screensaver and some configuration/setup tasks — across many short sessions rather than long deep-dives. With 277 messages across 19 sessions but only 3 total hours, your sessions average under 10 minutes each, suggesting you **dip in and out frequently**, sometimes exiting before work is complete or even before making a request. You rely heavily on Bash and Read tools for exploration, and you've experimented with advanced features like TaskCreate (9 uses), memory observer agents, and MCP/Serena plugins, indicating you're actively pushing the boundaries of what Claude Code can do rather than using it as a simple coding assistant.\n\nYour interaction style shows a pattern of **giving high-level directives and expecting Claude to figure out the details**, which leads to frequent misunderstandings — 10 instances of misunderstood requests is your top friction category. For example, Claude confused your question about Mac plugins with Code plugins, and struggled to identify which project you wanted analyzed. You also tend to **move on quickly when things aren't working** rather than providing additional context, as seen when you exited sessions about remote control troubleshooting and startup hook errors before resolution. The clock project is revealing: you iterated across multiple sessions to get visual details right (Roman vs Arabic numerals, font choices, minute marker positioning), correcting Claude's output against reference images rather than specifying every detail upfront. This **visual refinement loop** — build, compare to reference, correct — is central to how you work.\n\nNotably, you've set up a fairly sophisticated workflow with memory observer agents running alongside primary sessions and Serena MCP integration, though these **infrastructure investments haven't fully paid off yet** — several observer sessions produced minimal value. Your 6 instances of \"wrong approach\" friction and only 1 commit across 19 sessions suggest you're still in an experimental phase with your tooling setup, prioritizing learning the system over shipping code.",
