# Claude Code Insights

65 sessions total · 19 analyzed · 277 messages · 3h · 1 commits
2026-02-12 to 2026-03-03

## At a Glance

**What's working:** You have a disciplined, task-driven approach to projects—breaking your Bauhaus clock screensaver into numbered tasks and working through them sequentially got you to a production-ready app. Your willingness to iterate on visual details across sessions, comparing against reference images and filing precise fixes, shows a strong design sensibility that pairs well with Claude's code editing. See _Impressive Things You Did_.

**What's hindering you:** On Claude's side, it frequently misinterprets what you're referring to—especially when concepts cross product boundaries (like Mac plugins vs Code plugins) or when you reference something Claude can't see, leading to wasted back-and-forth. On your side, short or abandoned sessions and light-context requests (referencing errors or images without spelling out details) make it harder for Claude to deliver on the first try, particularly for visual tasks where the first implementation rarely matches what you have in mind. See _Where Things Go Wrong_.

**Quick wins to try:** Try creating a custom `/build-check` skill for your Swift workflow so you don't have to manually verify builds after each change. You could also add hooks to auto-run your build command after file edits, catching compiler issues immediately instead of discovering them later in the session. See _Features to Try_.

**Ambitious workflows:** As models improve, imagine handing Claude your full task pipeline (like Tasks 5 through 7) and having it autonomously implement, build, test, and commit each one—only surfacing when blocked. For visual work, future models will be able to build, screenshot, and compare against your spec in a loop, catching style mismatches before you ever review. See _On the Horizon_.

